comment:
The grammar of "The visualization is..." constrains the way I can express the terms, so some of my responses don't quite make grammatical senses, but I hope you get the drift.

I strongly believe aesthetics is much more than "looks nice", and feel that "how it looks" cannot be separated from "what it does". I like Ge Wang's description of aesthetics from his book Artful Design:

"Aesthetics is how we experience a thing â€”how it emotionally, intellectually, psychologically, and socially affects us. It is everything beyond the thing's function. Yet aesthetics does not usurp or live apart from functionality; instead, it gives context, meaning, and essence to a thing, making it what it is.

In the kitchen of design, aesthetics is not the spice with which you garnish the casserole of functionality: it is the casserole, the ingredients you bake into it."
Memorability does not exactly fit, but it also comes to my mind and thus could be related

vis001[SQ005]: Looks great, but does not enable to get insight
vis001[SQ007]: Shows complete ignorance of human visual perception
comment: Looking forward to the next round!

The "is" makes this very challenging, likely intentional.
I can think of no better term than "beautiful.
I would not use a Lickert scale to quantify aesthetic quality with seven ordered categories. I would use methods for analysing qualitative reactions, But good luck in your efforts to enumerate.

vis001[SQ006]: well crafted in terms of graphic design

comment: Those terms do not seem specific to visualization aesthetics, but aesthetics in general.   Other terms that may apply:  simple, streamlined, clear, pleasing to the eye, painterly, fun, engaging
Very interesting and fun study.  It's clear why you are conducting this as it's hard to come up with abbreviated terms.
Aesthetics borders many other types of attributes. I would be generic and try to capture also neighbouring attributes.

All of these might be invertible as well (e.g., visually displeasing). Terms related to specific affective or reference-based (e.g., most romantic, most fauvist, etc.) could also be applied, but seems like it opens a whole can of worms in the context above.
Given that aesthetics falls in that sort of weird world of "beauty is in the eye of the beholder", I'm not sure any scale will easily capture that.
